BEGIN_PGML Evaluate the definite integral
[``` \int_{ 0 } ^ { \pi } [$a1] \sin(x)\,dx\text{.}```]
[_]{$ans}{30}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION This integration can be done because we know that the derivative with respect to [`x`] of [`\cos(x)`] is [`-\sin(x)\text{.}`] So we obtain a [`-\sin(x)`] inside the integral, and we can then integrate to obtain [`\cos(x)\text{.}`] Of course, since there isn't a minus sign inside the integral, we'll have to multiply inside and outside by [`-1`] (which doesn't change the value of course):
[``` \begin{aligned} \int_0^\pi [$a1] \sin(x)\,dx &= -[$a1] \int_0^\pi (-\sin(x))\,dx\\ &= -[$a1] \left( \left. \cos(x) \right|_0^\pi \right)\\ &= -[$a1] ( \cos(\pi) - \cos(0) ) = -[$a1] (-1-1) = 2 \cdot [$a1] = [$ans]
\end{aligned} ```]
END_PGML_SOLUTION
