statement.p:
Compute the value of the following improper integral.  If it is divergent, type "Diverges" or "D".
\int_{0}^{2}\! \frac{dx}{x^{2}-6x+5}
Answer:

static.solution:
Solution:
Substitute x = r \tan{\theta}, so that
u = Ar \displaystyle\int_{a}^{\infty} \frac{\hbox{d}x}{(r^2+x^2)^{(3/2)}} = Ar \displaystyle\int_{a}^{\infty} \frac{r\sec^2{\theta} \hbox{d}\theta}{(r^2(1+\tan^2{\theta}))^{(3/2)}}
Then, since \displaystyle\int \frac{r\sec^2{\theta} \hbox{d}\theta}{(r^2(1+\tan^2{\theta}))^{(3/2)}} = \displaystyle\int \frac{r\sec^2{\theta} \hbox{d}\theta}{(r^2(1+\tan^2{\theta}))(r^2(1 + \tan^2{\theta}))^{(1/2)}} = \displaystyle\int \frac{\hbox{d}\theta}{r^2\sec{\theta}} = \frac{1}{r^2} \sin{\theta} using a trig identity.
Then since x = r \tan{\theta} = r \displaystyle\frac{\sin{\theta}}{\cos{\theta}} we see \sin{\theta} = \displaystyle\frac{x}{r}\cos{\theta} = \displaystyle\frac{x}{r\sec{\theta}} = \displaystyle\frac{x}{r\sqrt{1+ \tan^2{\theta}}} = \frac{x}{\sqrt{r^2 + x^2}}
Finally, u = \lim_{b\to\infty} \frac{A}{r}\left[\frac{x}{\sqrt{r^2+x^2}}\right]_{a}^{b} = \frac{A}{r}\left(1-\frac{a}{\sqrt{r^2+a^2}}\right)

