statement.p:
Note that when the constant in the denominator is not 1, we still can use the geometric series, but we have to multiply by
a form of 1 that helps us.  We'll use \frac{\frac{1}{4}}{\frac{1}{4}}.
\frac{1}{(4+x)}=\frac{\frac{1}{4}}{\frac{1}{4}(4+x)}=\frac{\frac{1}{4}}{1+\frac{1}{4}x}=\frac{1}{4}\cdot \frac{1}{1+\frac{1}{4}x}

